body:
I'm driving gulp from [gradle](http://www.gradle.org/) (a Java build tool) in cases where the developer is primarily a Java-type developer and wants to keep their workflow Java-based.  Obvisouly, the point of this is that gulp is the best build tool for the web tier and yet gradle is already doing build stuff and 'watch-like' behavior.

There is a trick, though.  I have to read the streams coming out of the node process and write them through the java process to the console.  And node detects my reader isn't a tty and therefore chalk doesn't emit color coded text.

I've managed to wrangle it.  **Would be nice if it (forcing colors to be used) was somehow supported in the next version of the gulp's log support.  That's my feature request.**

Here's my solution, which hopefully bears no resemblance to how this would be supported in future gulp loggers.   I create seperate module, runGulp.js:

``` javascript
'use strict';

// does the caller want to force color coding?
var forceColor = require('minimist')(process.argv.slice(2))['force-color'];

if (forceColor) {
  var chalk = require('chalk');
  // force color coding if requested
  chalk.enabled = chalk.enabled || true;


  // force color coding on plugins
  var pkg = require('./package.json');
  var sections = ['dependencies', 'peerDependencies', 'devDependencies'];
  var pattern = /^gulp-.+$/;

  // loop the sections of the package.json looking for gulp- plugins
  sections.forEach(function(section) {
    var sec = pkg[section];
    if (sec) {
      Object.keys(sec).forEach(function(dep) {
        if (pattern.test(dep)) {
          // if it's a gulp plugin and it has a gulp-util dependency,
          // match color support to overall chalk setting
          try {
            var colors = require(dep + '/node_modules/gulp-util').colors;
            colors.enabled = true;
          }
          catch (err) {}
        }
      });
    }
  });
}

// run the gulp client as if we were never here... :)
require('gulp/bin/gulp');
```

Then I invoke it with `node runGulp` from gradle.
